answer.value:
The scales on the right hand side of the screen are not accurate guides to the number of tweets or followers or the account ages that appear in tooltips when the bars are hovered over. For example, if the scale is 0 to 1000, some of the bars will look like they are just under 1000, but they are actually meant to represent a number larger than that, like Jeffrey's followers at 1194.
Other than that, the only odd thing that stands out to me is that EVis19 has a lot of interactions for a new account with few tweets or followers.

The answer was clear once I did this, but some option to have the program automatically do this for me would make it much easier.

S-task15.prompt: Of the North Americans who are two interactions away from Sereno, who has been on twitter the longest?

answer.value: It seems that the people with multiple connections mostly connect to one person, and the chain dead-ends there.  Some of them, like Alex and Jeffrey, also have few tweets, which is interesting for how many connections and followers they have, as well as for how old their account is.  It appears that most European people interact with everyone, while North American people tend to form small groups of other North Americans, like with Rob, Lane, and Jeffrey.

feedback.explanation: It was slightly hard to come up with something to comment on, but having done all of the previous tasks, I was familiar with what the layout meant, so I could extrapolate some thoughts.

answer.value: The person with the oldest account (Lynn) has very few interactions within the network, but a relatively large number of followers and tweets. The institutions generally seem to have fewer tweets than the people, but they also seem to be more likely to have a large number of followers in spite of having few tweets (with a few exceptions, people with few tweets generally have few followers). It also seems that the European accounts seem to have more of a tendency to have few followers and few tweets -- maybe this suggests that Twitter is less widely-used in their countries?

In general, this seems like a very efficient way to display and examine data. The study was very enjoyable overall!

answer.value: I'm so confused about what is going on. This network is very difficult for me to understand. It isn't too hard to navigate some of the simple questions, but I when I look at the network without any questions to guide me, I don't see anything interesting or surprising. It looks like there is an interesting cluster in the bottom right corner, but I don't understand what that means or if it is significant. The visual web used at the beginning of this survey was much easier to understand.

overallFeedback.overall: This was a lot more difficult than I was anticipating. Although there were some easy questions, the hard questions were very hard. It was kind of stressful for me because I didn't know how to answer and I didn't want to answer wrong.

training.explanation: I was following for the first half of the video, but I had to watch the second half twice. It was quite confusing as I don't know very much about multivariate networks. It would have been useful if the help button available during the tasks had more information. I forgot what certain terms meant, so I wasn't sure how to perform some of the tasks.

answer.value: GiCentre has interacted with itself 10 times. MViews has gained a lot of followers in a short amount of time, despite having no mentions and few tweets (bot followers?). Accounts from North America seem to have more followers, on average than those from South America, the EU, or Asia. There doesn't seem to be as much correlation between Account age and followers as there is between tweets and followers. Even tweets and followers aren't very closely correlated. Jeffrey has the most followers but not anywhere near the most tweets. He may have the largest cluster, however.

answer.value:

Jeffrey belongs to a large cluster where most interactions are directly through him. The nodes seem to be split between being individuals, or in large clusters. There are not many small clusters.

answer.value:
The cluster has more people than institutions, and are mostly made up of NA and EU users. It has a very high average account age and follower counts, but tweets are more variable.

There are is a section of people who have only interacted with Jeffrey, but most of the people he interacted with are from outside of the cluster. Jeffrey also has the highest follower count.

Robert also has a high number of accounts that he interacted with, but they are split between the cluster and outside of it.

Krist has the most tweets. Lynn has the oldest account. But both of these users have very few interactions within the network, despite having high numbers in all fields (followers, tweets, account age).

When sorted by continent, EU users form almost the outline of a cube through their interactions.

answer.value: I find it interesting that Jeffrey has the most followers, and a decent number of neighbors, at 27. I also think it's interesting his neighbors are primarily North American and European, and mostly persons and not institutions. This makes me wonder of persons in developed countries have more access to Twitter, and if this is why Jeffrey's followers consist of persons from that region.

answer.value: I am astonished by how many interactions does every person on this network have with each other. It feels incredibly interconnected. Also, there are some people who are are extremely social, like robert and alex, while others only interact with only one or two people. I would expect institutions to have more interactions overall, after all, they are formed by a wide variety of people who have different networks. And finally, it suprises me the fact that almost everyone on this network is active in twitter and have hundreds of followers, interactions, likes and tweets.

overallFeedback.overall: Was a quite fairly interesting data ''game'', useful for teaching children in primary school etc. how strong social media is and the influence certain people can have. Basically you’re a node in a network. Of course that’s even more true now that we have social media. You’ll know a thousand people at least over the course of your life, and they’ll know a thousand people each, and that puts you one person away from a million, and two persons away from a billion. And so that’s how you’re connected, and the things you do is like dropping a stone in a pond. The ripples move outward, and they affect things in ways that you can’t fully comprehend.

answer.value:
It is surprising the the network has an obvious 'nucleus' of contributors, and then such an array of outliers. For example, Helwig only interacts with Thomas. Unsurprisingly those outliers have the fewest followers and often tweets. 

However looking towards the centre of the diagram - where you see the most nodes, you would expect to see a correlation between tweets and follows (e.g. like Robert), but that isn't always the case. Tamara, MViews and EEyes have lots of tweets but not a correspondingly high number of followers. 

Most users tend to be from North America or Europe - there also tend to be geographical clusters. Maybe time difference and real-time interactions still have a bearing in the digital age?

It also appears institutions have fewer followers overall than people. Interesting!

feedback.explanation: Not sure about confidence on this one as it's a freetext field, but there was plenty of interesting information that could be drawn out from the diagram when you look around!
